segments.text: Mentioning people, and I'll start with mentioning people in the planning department that have made some contributions over the years.
And I'll just, currently Mike O'Neill is the head of current planning at the planning department.
And Mike worked a lot on the land use plan and many of the changes in the land use regulations
San Antonio has received some credit for, particularly dealing with issues of affordable housing and other things.
So he's certainly someone that has and is making a contribution today.
Oh, I'm bad at names.
Well.

Wendell Davis, who is no longer with the planning department, and he's got his own firm, Wendell Davis and Associates, and also a firm called Essay Research, both in San Antonio, was kind of the principal planner during the period of the chapter four and all of that era, and worked on a lot of it, and didn't necessarily support
some of the things that the planning department was doing and probably be a good person to talk to about many of the things that went on.
He also worked closely with, during this period of time, the city was attempting to get some feel for the cost of growth, because that was also an issue.
So Gruen and Gruen and Newport Economic Group and others were retained as consultants.
And many of those studies
I think are significant in terms of the evolution of the planning department itself.
God, thinking back, it's hard to remember all those people over the years and what they
Probably the way to do this systematically is the biography or the bibliography I gave you has got most of the documents listed.
We'd really have to go in and look at who were the, because most of those documents list the staff and who was the key staff person involved in some of those things.
As I mentioned, Stromberg earlier is one of the main people behind the whole
gross sketch and gross study.
Drumber moved on to Colorado.
Yeah, last I knew he was in some city suburb of Denver, but that was a number of years ago.
I don't know where he ended up.
Yeah, well I do want to make sure that the principal and senior planners who made impacts on
city planning in the various cities of Texas, as well as just the planning directors and mayors.
Now, considering the whole panorama of planning in San Antonio, what do you consider to be the five or so major planning events in San Antonio's history?
Well, I'm not sure that these would classify as events.
Well, if you're looking at it in an objective sort of way, I'd have to say that the Bartholomew plan
its adoption was certainly significant.
Obviously, extremely significant was the adoption of the charter with that very strong pro-planning Article 9, which is probably as strong a mandate as any city has in Texas,
given the fact that state statute is silent.
I think the splitting of the Planning and Zoning Commission in 1976 to really start the whole movement toward a plan was also a significant event.
I think the adoption of the basic plan

which not the event itself in August of 1980 as much as what it represented in the community and that was that the community over a period of three or four years had turned around from a position where there was a lot of disagreement about the legitimacy of a city doing planning to more recently almost near unanimity
about the role of a city in dealing with growth and development through a plan.

I think when you see a new chairman of the Greater San Antonio Chamber of Commerce take office and one of his opening statements is, you know, pro-City of San Antonio doing planning, you know things have really started turning around.
the adoption of the Basic Plan kind of symbolized that type of thing.
Another event I think is just the appointment of Ed Davis as Director of Planning and his influence, although even today it may be hard to judge what that influence actually is, but I do think that
that represented a substantial change in terms of the professional staff and professionalism in city planning in San Antonio.
So those are some things that I think are significant.
Has state government had any appreciable impact on planning in San Antonio?
Well, only in terms of events, not in terms of...
of providing technical assistance or providing specific legislative abilities.
What I mean by events are things like, and I'm sure Kathy Powell talked with you about this, but the whole aquifer controversy.
that in San Antonio basically focused on the period about 1975 through 1979.
And the state had a role in that basically because of the Texas Water Quality Board and all that.
And we see the state dealing with events as opposed to anything else in plain in San Antonio.
And then, of course, the location of the university campus.
But see, most of San Antonio's planning, since we lacked a plan until relatively recently, has been a reactive type of thing.
You know, there have been major controversies, and it's not just, you know, everything from urban renewal controversies with the San Antonio new town in town,
in the early 1970s, to things like the aquifer in the mid-70s, to San Antonio Ranch Newtown, and they just go on and on and on, and still to a certain extent go on over specific projects.
Well, and then of course one would have to ask the state's impact on planning in San Antonio regarding the location of freeways.
Well, except that most of the... Well, I guess I'd say two things.
A, is that the freeway thing has been a positive impact overall.
And B, is that lately, the last decade or two, it's been a cooperative effort.
In other words, the state has not come in and said, here's the way it's going to be.
In fact,
I think at San Antonio our expressway system is as good, and I think better, than any that exists in the state of Texas, and probably as good as any in the country.
And that came about because of cooperation, not the state mandating that this is the way it's going to be.
And that's evidenced by some of the things that are going on with expressways now in San Antonio.
Now, even the state is not in the role as the initiator.
It's the local community.
You would say that the history of freeway location has largely been a cooperative effort in San Antonio.
I think it has, and I think that obviously there are problems.
I mean, you know, roads were located
that created problems in terms of certain specific neighborhoods.
But in the era of the urban expressway in this country, I challenge anyone to name a city in which that didn't occur.
The overall system, where it's located and how it functions today I think is good.
And I think that the community has resisted, and there are examples of this,
has resisted expressways.
In other words, not every expressway that was proposed got built.
There were big controversies over the Bandera Expressway.
There were major controversies over the Macalester Expressway.
So I mean, it's not like they haven't been controversial.
In fact, the Macalester Expressway is an indication of 20 or 25 years classic example of a controversy.
But there, the controversy was not necessarily the state against the city.
But it was various factions in the city fighting over it.
I think the state role is a positive role.
What are the main administrative procedures and planning program elements that San Antonio has for implementing community plans?
You've already mentioned, of course, the usual.
subdivision review and so on.
And basically that's what they are.
I mean, you've got the traditional mechanisms of San Antonio, zoning, subdivision, capital improvements, codes, and then a lot of projects.
I think the San Antonio has been on the cutting edge in terms of working cooperatively with the private sector to get things done.
We see
For example, downtown San Antonio, which was a high priority and has been in most of the plans, its rejuvenation was due largely to the city's leadership and cooperation with the private sector.
San Antonio has also, I think, largely been on the cutting edge in looking at new mechanisms.
You know, talk about historic districts or talk about airport

military airport zoning or talk about tax assessment districts or tax increment financing or all these types of things San Antonio has I think at least in Texas been on the cutting edge of either using those mechanisms or being the one that really pushed the state to allow cities to get them and then they're using them once the state has got them it's also worked very cooperatively with

the federal government to get things done, the creation of the San Antonio Missions National Historic Park, the protection of the military airport in San Antonio, a lot of flood control projects, and the cooperative things between the city of San Antonio, the San Antonio River Authority, and the Army Corps of Engineers.
So I think San Antonio's gone a long way beyond the traditional mechanisms.
And these administrative procedures are certainly not all within the planning department.
Oh, no.
In fact, when it comes to plan implementation, a lot of that occurs outside the planning department.
And in fact, see, the other thing you've got to realize is that it's only relatively recently that even the common planning implementing mechanisms have been within the planning department.
For a long time, zoning
was not a function that the planning department dealt with.
That was in a separate department of the city.
I recall that was that way, and Lila Conkroll was concerned about that relationship.
Yeah.
So actually, for a long time, we really had two planning departments, in essence.
We had a planning department, and let me just say that
that these came about because of the politics of the bureaucracy, as well as some structural problems.

One of the reasons, well let me just back up and say that for a long time we had two planning departments, one that dealt with long range planning, and then one that basically could be characterized as current planning, where zoning
and all of those types of things would be.
And they didn't really even get along with each other very well.
Were they housed in the same office?
Not even the same building.
They had different directors.
Okay.
We've talked a lot about San Antonio and its planning.
That's the topic.
Now we have come to the point that
San Antonio has a mayor who has a degree in planning.
And as such, has this made a difference in San Antonio?
Or if not, do you think it might in the future?
And in what way is Henry Cisneros' mayorship going to be significantly different than anyone else's?
Well, I'm not sure it's made a difference.
Let me say that I guess Henry had the opportunities that Hartman had to initiate and be very supportive of the planning function in San Antonio.
And I think that his overall record is one of cautious and
Well, cautious support, but it's also characterized by periods where frequently he'll just ignore the planning function.
Henry is the type of person that's much more oriented to projects and getting things done as opposed to the long-range planning type of effort that we're talking about.
And he was not the one that was responsible for the mid-'70s planning initiative, although he was supportive of it.
More recently, his Target 90 effort is an example of something that, although one could attribute that to his planning education, that we need goals,
The whole thing was done totally outside of and largely ignored the established planning function.
What he did was ended up almost going back to turn of the century planning in the United States and appointing a massive 500 person private citizen committee to come up with
Now, there were many beneficial things about that process, but I'm not sure that in terms of typical planning, that that's such a good idea.
Because you have in place, I mean, it wasn't that the city didn't have goals.
The city's got goals coming out the kazoo.
It's just that this was a separate type of effort, and it remains to be seen whether the target 90 ongoing process
actually accomplishes anything since frequently it's operating outside the planning structure that the city has established.
And that's characteristic of how Henry is operating.
He knows planning, but he's not interested in long-range stuff.
He's interested in getting stuff done, the project stuff.
Well, some people would argue that the
institutionalized planning process of local government is outside the realm of the decision-making process.
I would agree.
I'm even questioning the need for it.
We've had two other examples of goals, projects for major Texas cities, one in Corpus Christi and another in Dallas.
Well, don't forget Austin.
And Austin had one as a basis for their Austin Tomorrow plan, so-called.
And then, of course, the state of Texas as well.
And what has come of these goals programs is variable.
The one in Corpus Christi was an excellent program.
Unfortunately, it came to very little in their case.
Do you have a copy of the book?
Yes.
The goals for Texas, I think the fallout from that, I'm sorry, the goals for Dallas are going to be longer coming because of the politics of the Dallas situation.
But we'll have to see Marvin Springer's writings.
about that now.
And the goals for Texas, we know what happened to that.
And Austin is mixed.
It's mixed.
And they have yet to produce a full-blown plan.
All they have now is... Well, but their whole attitude has changed in terms of growth.
It really has.
And they have yet to produce...
Which is exactly what happened in San Antonio.
San Antonio's attitude changed about growth.
I was going to say, Austin has yet to produce a full-blown plan.
They have the makings of a plan, but it's not a complete plan.
All it is is a word plan filled with goals and objectives and policy statements.
And that was unsatisfactory for the council.
Well, but I'll also argue is that
is that the definition of what constitutes a plan or what works as a plan is changing.
And I'm not sure that... See, San Antonio doesn't have a picture plan.
And I'm not sure that, you know...
In many cases, a community can find a policies plan that works just as well.
I would argue that.
Well, I know you would.
I'm just saying that's the reality of many communities today.
Well, they're planning that that reality doesn't work in the case of Austin.
It's a good example.
Well, I don't think you can attribute that in Austin to the plan itself as much as you can attribute it to some incredible changes in terms of the politics.
Just like San Antonio, the political and the social and the economic environment of that community has changed so much.
and their attitudes about the role of local government and their ideas of growth have just changed.
And in Austin's case, they're still going through some evolutionary things.
Like today, it'll be interesting to see in Austin what happens with some elections, because there's some very clear-cut council races in Austin that revolve on those basic issues that
have been around since Friedman's day.
I have a question here regarding the use of consultants.
What has been the role of private planning consultants in San Antonio's various planning programs?
Well, over the years, in addition to assistance on the major planning efforts, San Antonio has used literally probably hundreds of consultants on specific types of planning projects.
SOM worked with the city on the major
River Corridor Study, the award-winning study.
The cities have used consultants more recently like Metcalf and Eddy out of Boston to work on the aquifer study.
It's used Gruen and Gruen out of California on its economic analysis.
It's used
Ross Hardies, O'Keeffe, Babcock, and Parsons out of Chicago, the big land use law firm, to work on the city's development code.
So there literally have been countless examples of consultants dealing with the city, both in terms of specific projects where it's designed, as well as development codes and things like that.
And San Antonio doesn't hesitate
to bring in.
More recently it was using Lane Kendig who wrote the book on performance zoning to come in and do some things.
So, you know, San Antonio has constantly used planning consultants.
Not so much the firm to come in and do a plan as much as
firms that have a particular expertise in the law or in zoning or in economics or in something else to come in and work with the planning department staff on a specific project or a plan element.
